The above considerations lead to the postulation of two critical heating rates for the dissolution of
a speciﬁc initial heat treatment state, as illustrated in Figure
. The ﬁrst of these is the lower critical
heating rate (LCHR), and the second is the upper critical heating rate (UCHR). The LCHR is postulated
to be the fastest heating rate at which the particular initial state can be dissolved completely during
heating to a certain maximum temperature T
(which must be above the solvus temperature of
the alloy). A potential further increase in this temperature in the solid state will reduce the LCHR.
If heating is carried out to T
at a rate slower than the LCHR, a complete solid solution will be
obtained during heating. The LCHR therefore has high technological importance. For a soft annealed
state of 6005A, we found indications that the LCHR is on the order of 0.01 K
